 how a number of social, economic, and cultural forces converged in the early 1900s to influence lawmakers and criminalize addiction. His research exposes how social concerns about drug addiction had less to do with the long pipe and shadowy den than with lobbying by medical professionals, a growing pharmaceutical industry, and concern about the morality and future of the nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDrug addiction -- Economic aspects -- Canada -- History. 0aDrug addiction -- Social aspects -- Canada -- History. 0aDrugs -- Law and legislation -- Canada -- History. 0aNarcotic laws -- Canada -- History. 0aOpium abuse -- Law and legislation -- Canada -- History. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311142000440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482921240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774829212423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774829212/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-142000-4  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles